items.title: Persoonia chamaepeuce
items.content_text: About 4 plants in this fenced biosite area between Middle Gully Road and the railway line south of Woodend. This is the third location for the Dwarf Geebung in the Macedon Ranges. Previously recorded in a gully at Barrm Birrm, Riddells Creek and along the rail line just south of the Macedon station. Not common in Macedon Ranges but may exist in other areas along the railway.

items.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. armeria
items.content_text: Last of the late flowers.

items.content_text: Just coming into flower - a bit late this year?

items.title: Gompholobium huegelii
items.content_text: End of flowering season - dried sepals remaining after fruits have fallen.

items.title: Cassinia aculeata
items.content_text:
Species information:
Erect shrub to about 3 m high.
Leaves spreading, linear, 10–50 mm long, 1–2.5 mm wide, cottony beneath.
Flowers heads, white, in large clusters.
Flowers Nov - Feb

items.title: Astroloma humifusum
items.content_text:
Species information:
Usually a mat-forming low shrub to 50 cm high.
Leaves 5–18 mm long, 0.6–3 mm wide, sharply pointed a tip, lower surface usually paler; margins toothed.
Flowers bright red, tubular, often hidden by the foliage.
Small sweet-tasting green-black berries.
Flowers Jan - July

items.title: Dipodium pardalinum
items.content_text: Many Dipodium pardalinum flowered over the Macedon area this year, although some were rather stunted.

items.title: Podolobium procumbens
items.content_text: Prostrate pea plant with attractive orange flowers.

items.title: Thysanotus patersonii
items.content_text: Twining Fringe-lily climbing up a plant. The leaves of the Fringe-lily are not in the photo - they are basal.

items.title: Thelymitra ixioides s.s.
items.content_text: Spotted sun-orchid with only one dark blue spot.

items.title: Caladenia moschata
items.content_text:
Photo showing the variation in height of plants in the same patch. (about 15cm to 30+ cm).
In this area the orchids had either greenish or red tinged flowers.

items.title: Caladenia transitoria
items.content_text:
A patch of a dozen or more plants, each about 12 cm tall. First record for Macedon Ranges. It is small and easily overlooked.
All had a single flower except two plants which had two flowers per stem.

items.title: Thelymitra peniculata
items.content_text: Leaves fleshy, distinctly ribbed on the outside. Apex of mid-lobe of column (yellow part) somewhat dorsally compressed with a V-notch. Lateral lobes of column with a terminal tuft of white hairs, extending horizontally and converging. More than 5 flowers per stem (I can count 7 or 8 including the buds).

items.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. armeria
items.content_text:
High resolution copy for first photo (habit). See "original" resolution. 
Note: Many plants in this area - all with white or very pale pink flowers instead of the more common deep pink to magenta colour.

items.title: Caladenia moschata
items.content_text: In my experience, Caladenia moschata can have a quite strongly vertically compressed dorsal sepal similar to C. cucullata but the second half of the labellum is not completely purple as in C. cucullata. I find that the detection of a strong musky scent is not a reliable feature.

items.title: Bossiaea prostrata
items.content_text: A great survivor hiding in the lawn. Lots of these peas still coming up in a lawn which has been closely mown for over 30 years. Spot the insect pollinator.

items.title: Pimelea linifolia subsp. linifolia
items.content_text: A very attractive display of Pimelea linifolia in relatively pristine woody grassland along the railway line at Macedon.(3 photos)

items.title: Cryptandra amara s.s.
items.content_text:
Close up of flowers, showing hood-like outgrowths of petals which closely cover the stamens. (Cryptandra = "hidden stamens").
Branchlets covered with fine stellate hairs. Leaves shortly petiolate, ovate to obovate or oblong, 2–5 mm long, 1–2 mm wide, mainly glabrous.

items.title: Pauridia vaginata
items.content_text: Glabrous herb. Leaves linear, flat, with irregularly spaced, small tooth-like outgrowths.

items.title: Daviesia leptophylla
items.content_text: Only a few plants in flower at this time.

items.title: Stackhousia monogyna s.s.
items.content_text: Early flowering

items.title: Acrotriche serrulata
items.content_text:
Species information:
Dense, prostrate to decumbent shrub to c. 30(–60) cm high; branchlets finely pubescent. 
Leaves linear-lanceolate to lanceolate, 3.5–11 mm long, 0.5–1.7 mm wide, with pointed tip (muronate).
Flowers, green-translucent, small, on old wood near the ground.
Flowers Jun - Nov

items.title: Acrotriche prostrata
items.content_text:
Species information: 
Trailing shrub with main stems prostrate and rooting at intervals, branches prostrate or ascending to about 15 cm high.
Leaves spreading, often more or less horizontal, lanceolate to ovate, 4–16 mm long, 1–8 mm wide, mucronate.
Flowers not obvious in dense c. 5–14-flowered spikes, on previous season's or older wood.
Flowers Apr - Jul

items.title: Acaena novae-zelandiae
items.content_text:
Spreading perennial to 20 cm high 
Flowers and fruits Sep - Apr

items.title: Persoonia chamaepeuce
items.content_text:
Many plants growing along the rail verge south of the Macedon station. 
In previous years only a  few plants have been observed at this location but now there would be 30 to 50 vigorous plants over a larger area.

Leaves rather thin, flat 2 - 6 mm wide, shiny bright green, hairless except for sparse hairs on margins of leaf

items.title: Alternanthera denticulata s.s.
items.content_text:
Trailing to weakly ascending annual or perenial
Stems to c. 50 cm long
Flowers in axillary spherical to ovoid spikes
Flowers most of year, mainly Oct - Jan

items.title: Blechnum wattsii
items.content_text:
Fronds spread along creeping rhizome to 125 cm tall 
Young fronds tinged pink to bronze 
Fertile fronds (two images lower right) commonly taller than sterile, pinnae linear, long.

items.title: Acacia stricta
items.content_text:
Species information:
Shrub or tree, 1–5 m high, often suckering; branchlets angled towards extremities, striate with yellowish resin ribs, glabrous. 
Phyllodes ascending to erect, normally linear to linear-oblanceolate, 3.5–14 cm long, 3–10(–15)mm wide, straight to shallowly curved, thin, glabrous, dull, green to grey-green or subglaucous, obtuse; midrib prominent.
Flower heads globular, 2-4 per leaf axil, cream to lemon-yellow, sometimes light golden, young buds mealy. 
Flowers mostly May - Oct

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. graveolens
items.content_text:
syn. Acacia verniciflua (southern variant)
Open shrub 2 - 5 m high.
Phyllodes (30–)50–110 mm long and (3–)7–20(–30) mm wide, puncticulate; with 2 longitudinal nerves on each face. Gland usually at distal end of pulvinus, (1–)2–4 mm above the pulvinus 
Flowers Aug - Nov

items.title: Pterostylis sp. aff. parviflora (Southern Victoria)
items.content_text: Characterised by its uncrowded, plump, rounded flowers that are brownish and scabrous towards the apex.

items.title: Lobelia pratioides
items.content_text: Growing at the back of the "lagoon", Black Forest Drive, Macedon

items.title: Olearia myrsinoides
items.content_text: Many plants have grown over this block  after a planned burn a year or so ago.

items.title: Acacia verticillata subsp. verticillata
items.content_text:
Species information:
Spreading shrub or erect tree, 2 - 5 m tall.
Phyllodes whorled, needle-like, 0.5–2.5 cm long, 0.5 -1.5 mm wide.
Flowers pale yellow to yellow, in cylindrical spikes, to 2 cm long, 1 - 3 spikes per leaf axil.
Flowers usually Jul.–Dec.

items.title: Acacia melanoxylon
items.content_text:
Species information: 
Small to large long-lived tree 6 - 30 m high. 
Phyllodes narrowly elliptic, lanceolate or oblanceolate, 4–16 cm long, 6–25 mm wide, main veins 3–5, raised, distant. Flower heads, cream to yellow in clusters of 2 to 5.
Seed black, encircled by pink fleshy tissue.
One of the most wide-ranging trees in eastern Australia.
Flowers Aug - Oct

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. uninervia
items.content_text:
Species information: Bushy or openly branched shrubs 2–5 m tall. Phyllodes mostly (40–)70–140 mm long, (6–)8–15(–18) mm wide; with 1 longitudinal nerve, the nerve prominent; lateral nerves few to numerous, often quite evident (at least when dry) and distally coalescing to form a fine, continuous but uneven intra-marginal nerve on one or both sides of the phyllode. 
Flowers from late August to early October.

items.title: Acacia gunnii
items.content_text:
Species information: Spreading, erect or prostrate shrub to 1 m high. 
Phyllodes variable but more or less asymmetrically triangular, with a spine.
Spherical creamy pale yellow flower heads on long peduncles, one per leaf axil.
Flowers Jun - Oct

items.title: Acacia dealbata subsp. dealbata
items.content_text:
Species information: Tree to 30 m high or spindly shrub.
Leaves grey bluish-green, bipinnate with a raised gland at the junction of each pinna pair.
Spherical flower heads, bright yellow in clusters of 25 - 35 .
Flowers Jul - Oct

items.title: Caladenia gracilis
items.content_text:
Grows to 30 cm tall 
2 to 6 flowers per plant 
Musk scented

items.title: Thelymitra rubra
items.content_text:
Note the yellow finger-like projections on the column lateral lobes. This together with the more salmon rather than pink colour, distinguishes it from the similar T.carnea (Pink Sun-orchid)
Colour was more salmon than captured in the photo.

items.title: Acacia ulicifolia
items.content_text:
Species information:
Erect, often straggly shrub, mostly 1–2 m high.
Phyllodes spreading, linear-triangular, 5–15 mm long, 0.5–1.5 mm wide, thorn-like.
Flower heads, globular, one per leaf axil, creamy yellow.
Flowers Apr - Oct.

items.title: Cardamine lilacina s.l.
items.content_text:
Cardamine lilacina ("Alpine" Bitter-cress) 
Perennial to 30 cm high 
Hairless leaves thin to fleshy 
Flowers most of year

items.content_text: Previously unrecorded in the Macedon Ranges

items.title: Drymophila cyanocarpa
items.content_text: Fruit (berry) is white becoming blue to purple as it matures in April.

items.title: Bossiaea buxifolia
items.content_text: Now Bossiaea decumbens (B. buxifolia Qld only)

items.title: Caladenia congesta
items.content_text:
Can grow to 50 cm - local specimens to 30 cm tall 
Up to 4 flowers per plant 
Single grass-like leaf at base 
Flowers Oct - Jan

items.title: Acacia nano-dealbata
items.content_text:
Species information:
Erect, large shrub or small tree, 2 - 6m tall
Green bipinnate leaves, *pinnules rounded at apex and touching or overlapping* (distinguishes from the similar looking Acacia dealbata)
Yellow spherical flower-heads in short racemes or large bunches
Listed rare in Australia
Flowers Mid-Winter

items.title: Acacia gunnii
items.content_text:
Acacia gunnii (Ploughshare Wattle)
Spreading, erect or prostrate shrub to 1 m high
Flowers Jun - Oct

items.title: Acianthus pusillus
items.content_text:
Species information: Orchid, 4 - 18 cm tall. Single leaf cordate, flat-to-ground, reddish-purple beneath.
Flowers 1–18, translucent green or pinkish with reddish veins and spots.
Flowers Apr - Aug.

items.title: Bedfordia arborescens
items.content_text:
Species information:
Shrub or small tree to 8 m high.
Leaves mostly 10 - 25 cm long and 2 - 5 cm wide, upper surface green with impressed veins, lower surface white-wooly.
Flowers heads small, yellow in clusters.
Flowers Oct - Feb

items.title: Todea barbara
items.content_text: Note Short, massive black-brown fibrous trunk with many tufts of fronds. Trunk can grow to the size of a wine barrel or larger.

items.title: Acacia mucronata subsp. longifolia
items.content_text:
Species information:
Shrub or small tree to less than 5 m tall.
Phyllodes 9-20cm long, narrow-linear, with a short, sharp point(mucro), veins 3-4, often 1 more prominent than others, gland 5-10mm above axil.
Flowers clusters pale yellow, arranged in spikes 1-6cm long.
Flowers Aug-Dec.

items.title: Blechnum chambersii
items.content_text:
Fronds erect, firm in texture, 20 - 50 cm tall
Sterile and fertile fronds dissimilar
Fertile fronds erect, similar in length to sterile fronds but pinnae narrow and curved. 
Sori covering underside on each side of midvein.
